				<p><p>Cheap toy arms usually use cheap off the shelf servos, the kind you would find on model airplanes. Usually these servos don't have any control over speed. You give the servo the target angle and the servo tries to get to that position as fast as possible. They also don't compensate for things like load. With more expensive servos you give them both the target position and speed. There are also servos where you can play around with values (such as PID) and get information on things like load. This allows to to get smooth movement</p>
